  - the method should recall what it set as aim and query if that target changed



the new python-st3215 module:
- ST3215 is a wrapper providing methods to build/send/read/parse packages
  on a low-level mode (byte-strings, they are al sequences of bytes)
  - parse_response returns a dict with "parameters" = bytes sent by servo
  - returns Servo objects from wrap_servo() or broadcast = Servo(254)
  - sync_read/sync_write compile a package from servo_id: [int] mappings
    where the int are just all packed (using their least-significant btes)
- Servo object has the controller = ST3215 as one member
  - Servo.send: just wraps to ST3125.send_instruction
  - all low level, no word/byte encoding
  - has members eeprom and sram
  - _read_memory compiles response in effectively little-endian
- eeprom: read_firmware ... stuff that servos keep over reboot
  these seem to all use read/write_byte with just one byte
  - except angle limit -> read/write_word -> these encode
    and the encoders work effectively little-endian
- sram:
  - read_torque_switch -> read from 0x28=40 (SMS_STS_TORQUE_ENABLE)
  - write_torque_switch / torque_enable OK
  - set to 2048 -> via torque_enable writing 128 OK => correct_position_to_2048
  - read_target_location uses read_word(... signed=True)
  - read_running_speed as well, write_... as well
  - read_current_speed DOES NOT USE signed=True !?
- commands in use, mapped to C-code SMS_STS_
  eeprom:
  firmware_major_version: 0x00 = 0 = (not impl)
  firmware_minor_version: 0x01 = 1 = (not impl)
  servo_main_version: 0x03 = 3 = SMS_STS_MODEL_L
  servo_version: 0x04 = 4 = SMS_STS_MODEL_H
  id: 0x05 = 5 = SMS_STS_ID
  baudrate: 0x06 = 6 = SMS_STS_BAUD_RATE (0..7)
  return_delay: 0x07 = 7 = (not impl) delay in 2µs units 0..508 = 254
  response_status_level: 0x08 = 8 = (not impl) 1: return response for all commands, not just read/ping
  min_angle_limit: 0x09 = 9 = SMS_STS_MIN_ANGLE_LIMIT_L
    probably 0x0a = 10 = SMS_STS_MIN_ANGLE_LIMIT_H is the high byte for that
  max_angle_limit: 0x0b, 0x0c = 11, 12 = SMS_STS_MAX_ANGLE_LIMIT_L,H
  max_temperature_limit: 0x0d = 13 = (not impl)
  max_input_voltage: 0x0e = 14 = (not impl)
  min_input_voltage: 0x0f = 15 = (not impl)
  max_torque (word): 0x10, 0x11 = 16,17 = (not impl)
  etc... more stuff on pwm mode
  operating_mode: 0x21 = 33 = SMS_STS_MODE

  sram:
  torque_switch: 0x28 = 40 = SMS_STS_TORQUE_ENABLE
  acceleration: 0x29 = 41 = SMS_STS_ACC
  target_location: 0x2A, 0x2B = 42,43 = SMS_STS_GOAL_POSITION_L,H
  runtime: 0x2C, 0x2D = 44, 45 = GOAL_TIME (used in PWM mode? bit 10 = direction)
  running_speed: 0x2E, 0x2F = 46, 47 = GOAL_SPEED
  torque_limit: 0x2A, 0x2B = 48, 49 = TORQUE_LIMIT
  lock_symbol: 0x37 = 55 = LOCK (to lock eeprom)
  sram readonly (?):
  read_current_location: 0x38, 0x39 = 56, 57 = PRESENT_POSITION
  read_current_speed: 0x3A, 0x3B = 58, 59 = PRESENT_SPEED
  read_current_load: 0x3C, 0x3D = 60, 61 = PRESENT_LOAD
  read_current_voltage: 0x3E = 62 = PRESENT_VOLTAGE
  read_current_temperature: 0x3F = 63 = PRESENT_TEMPERATURE
  read_async_write_flag 0x40 = 64 = ??
  read_servo_status 0x41 = 65 = ??
  read_mobile_sign 0x42 = 66 = MOVING
  read_current_current 0x45, 0x46 = 69, 70 = PRESENT_CURRENT



i need: wheel -> eeprom.write_operating_mode(1)
        pos   -> eeprom.write_operating_mode(0)
        setmiddle -> sram.write_torque_switch(128)
        is_moving -> sram.read_mobile_sign
        read up on servo torque (sram.write_torque_switch(0 or 1) = torque_enable/torque_disable)

baud rate:
            int: Baud rate code (0-7), where:
                 0 = 1,000,000 baud
                 1 = 500,000 baud
                 2 = 250,000 baud
                 3 = 115,200 baud
                 4 = 57,600 baud
                 5 = 38,400 baud
                 6 = 19,200 baud
                 7 = 9,600 baud

operating mode: 0 pos control, 1 wheel (const speed), 2 pwm open-loop, 3 stepper servo



